Gatys et al Summary
Introduction:
The paper introduced the concept of ‘Style Transfer’ inspired by the way humans create art works by applying various different styles to the same content. The idea was to build on the existing CNN (VGGnet) architecture to separate the content and style of any given image.
Methodology:
The process was broken into 2 parts. One is content generation and the other is style generation. For the content generation, the VGG 19 architecture only encodes high level content that retains the features like the object, arrangement, shape etc. and low-level details are thrown out. Feature map activations from only 1 layer from these high level encodings were extracted by the researchers to represent the content.
For the style, low level encodings were used as there’s no need of the shape and size details anymore. This captured the brushstrokes, texture etc. Here’s where Gram matrices were introduced. Gram matrix is used to find the correlation between the feature map activation. So, instead of the location details of a pixel, we can know how are different pixels related to each other. This was used to identify the texture and other styles of the art/image. For n filters we have  each filter that produces a feature map of m spatial positions. Flatten each filter's map into a vector of length m. The Gram matrix entry Gij is just the dot product of filter i's vector with filter j's vector. This is similar to a corelation matrix.
For actual image synthesis on any desired input, they used gradient descent to adjust pixel values to match both content and style. A loss function was represented as sum of total loss in content + style:
 				L(total)  =  alpha*L(content) + beta*L(style)
Here, alpha and beta determined the weightage given to style and content in the expected output image. 

Observation and Conclusion:
The output images, which used works of artists like van Gogh and Picasso, had perfectly preserved the content as well as the applied style.  The alpha/beta ratio gave a smooth way to control the weightage in the image for content focussed or style focussed. 


AdaIn Summary
Intro:
The previous paper did work on the style transfer method, but it had one problem, of being slow. It works by optimizing pixel values through hundreds of gradient descent steps for every single imagethat's why it takes minutes even on a GPU.  Also, to use a different style on the same image, the model would be trained from scratch.
The AdaIn paper proposes method to apply arbitrary styles, at higher training speeds. They pre-normalize training images to remove contrast differences, then to remove style differences entirely, and watch how much IN still helps in each case. The improvement from IN almost vanishes once images are already style-normalized. They found that it isn't just doing contrast normalization, it's implicitly normalizing away an image's style.

Methodology:
The encoder is a fixed, pre-trained VGG-19 model, only the decoder has to be trained. It's trained to invert the AdaIN output back into a real image, using two losses:
Content loss: rather than comparing the output to the original content image's features (as Gatys does), they compare it to the AdaIN output itself that the target the decoder is supposed to reconstruct. This converges slightly faster and fits the decoder's actual job.
Style loss: Since AdaIN only transfers mean and standard deviation, the style loss also only matches mean and standard deviation of the output's features against the style image's features (across several VGG layers) not the full Gram matrix from Gatys. They found this works about as well but is conceptually cleaner, since it directly reflects what AdaIN is actually aligning.
The training used MS-COCO photos as content and WikiArt paintings as style with ~80,000 examples with random 256×256 crops. Crucially, the network never memorizes specific styles and only learns a general function for imposing any style's statistics onto any content.

Observation:
Speed: the paper reports it's roughly three orders of magnitude faster than the Gatys optimization approach, and one to two orders of magnitude faster than another patch-matching-based method, while still handling arbitrary, never-before-seen styles.
Quality: competitive with both the slow optimization method and with feed-forward networks that had to be trained on one specific style.
Content–style trade-off: interpolate between the raw content features and the AdaIN output before decoding where we can balance between how much it looks like the art, and how much like the photo being used.
Style interpolation: blend multiple styles at once by taking a weighted combination of their AdaIN outputs.
Color preservation and spatial control: apply AdaIN separately to different regions or match color statistics first, letting users stylize only parts of an image or preserve the original color palette.

10 year survey of recent developments in style transfer
Introduction:
This paper is a survey that reviews the last ten years of research on AI based style transfer. It covers more than 500 papers published between 2015 and 2025. The authors describe style transfer as a process that takes a content image and a style image and produces a new image that keeps the structure of the content while adopting the visual appearance of the style. The survey identifies three main stages in the field. The first stage began with Neural Style Transfer, which showed that a CNN can separate content and style. The second stage introduced faster methods, including feed forward networks and GANs, that could apply styles more quickly and to a wider range of images. The third stage, from 2022 to 2025, is dominated by diffusion models and autoregressive models, which allow high resolution results and more precise control, including control through text prompts.
Methodology:
The paper does not run new experiments. Instead, it collects and organizes existing research. It explains the mathematical basis of style transfer, including the content loss, the Gram matrix style loss from the original Gatys method, and the simpler mean and variance based loss used in AdaIN. It then reviews the major families of generative models used for style transfer, including Variational Autoencoders, Generative Adversarial Networks, flow matching models, autoregressive models, and diffusion models, explaining the basic idea and objective function behind each one. The authors also propose a framework for evaluating style transfer methods, based on categories such as visual quality, content preservation, diversity, computational efficiency, and ethical concerns. Finally, they organize hundreds of methods, datasets, and applications into tables sorted by year, covering areas such as portrait style transfer, video style transfer, 3D style transfer, and text style transfer.
Observations and Results:
The survey shows a clear trend over time. Early methods were accurate but slow, since they required an optimization process for every new image. Later methods became much faster by training a network in advance, though early fast methods were often limited to a single fixed style. Newer diffusion and autoregressive models offer more flexibility and higher quality, but they come with new trade offs. Diffusion models are good at producing realistic textures and can be guided easily with text or other signals, but they can lose fine structural details or introduce unwanted changes to the content. Autoregressive models tend to preserve structure and layout more precisely, but they are harder to guide with external style signals during generation. The paper also points out that there is still no single reliable way to measure how well a stylized image matches human perception, so researchers combine several different metrics. Finally, the authors highlight ongoing challenges, including high computational cost, the need for better text guided control, and ethical issues such as copyright, misuse of the technology, and respectful use of cultural or artistic styles.

Differentiating between Gatys et al and AdaIn:
1. Gram-matrix style loss in Gatys
Gatys defines style as correlations between filter responses. For each layer, every filter's output map gets flattened into a vector, and the Gram matrix is built from the dot product of every pair of those vectors​. This is a second-order statistic i.e it doesn't just record how active each filter is, it records how active pairs of filters are together. The style loss, then, is the squared difference between the generated image's Gram matrix and the target painting's Gram matrix, summed across several layers. To make this loss small, there's no closed-form shortcut: you have to run gradient descent on the pixels of the image itself, over hundreds of iterations, until the Gram matrix converges. The richness of the Gram matrix (all those pairwise filter correlations) is exactly what makes it expensive to satisfy.
2. Channel-wise mean and variance alignment in AdaIN
Huang & Belongie replace that in the AdaIn. Now, for each feature channel, just match its mean and its standard deviation to the style image's mean and standard deviation for that same channel. This is a first-order statistic, one number for average intensity and one for spread, per channel, done independently per channel with no pairwise interaction between channels. Because this is so simple, it isn't computed as a loss to be minimized iteratively. The style loss during training then also just matches means and standard deviations (not full Gram matrices), which the authors note gives similar results to Gram-matrix matching but is cleaner given what AdaIN is actually doing.
3. Improvement from pixel by pixel 
Because Gram matrix matching has no shortcut, Gatys' method must optimize pixels from scratch for every new content and style pair. There is no way to copy a Gram matrix onto an image, since matching correlational structure across an entire image is itself an iterative problem that must be solved step by step. Mean and variance, by contrast, can be copied in one step. AdaIN sits inside a network as a pipeline with three parts: a fixed encoder, the AdaIN layer, and a learned decoder. The encoder measures the content and style statistics, AdaIN swaps them directly, and the decoder, which is trained once in advance, converts the result back into pixels in a single forward pass. Nothing needs to be optimized at test time.
